Metropolitan and micropolitan statistical areas: 2 for MetropolitanSA, 1 for MicropolitanSA, 0 otherwise; MicropolitanSA didn't exist prior to 2000. (Coding and Source:  June 30 1993 "Metropolitan Areas and Components," is used for 1995-1998; June 30 1999 "Metropolitan Areas and Components" is used for 1999; June 2003 "Metropolitan and micropolitan statistical areas and components" is inputted for 2000-2003, because this delineation is based on 2000 decennial census; then "Metropolitan and micropolitan statistical areas and components" is available for each year, 2004-2009, https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/demo/metro-micro/historical-delineation-files.html // Feb 2013 "Core based statistical areas (CBSAs), metropolitan divisions, and combined statistical areas (CSAs)" is used for 2010-2014, because this delineation is based on 2010 decennial census; Jul 2015 "Core based statistical areas (CBSAs), metropolitan divisions, and combined statistical areas (CSAs)" is used for 2015, https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/demo/metro-micro/delineation-files.html) // No changes from 2010 through 2015 // No changes from 2000 through 2009 // Twin Falls became MetroSA in 2017.

Population Density // RAND State Statistics => Current Population Density; Descriptions: "Summary: Current population density based on land area"; "Additional Background: This database reports recent population density figures (persons per square mile) based on annual population, estimated on July 1st of each year, and land area reported by the U.S. Census.  Density from 1990-1999 is based on 1990 land area; 2000-2013 density is based on land area in each of those years."; "Geographic Coverage: U.S., States, Counties, City or Other Local Government, Periodicity: Annually, Series Begins/Ends: 1990 - 2017, Data Source: U.S. Bureau of the Census" // Units: Persons per square mile // PARKLINE CITY Disincorporated in 2001

Personal income per capita // Unit: dollars, current // Measurement Level: County // Source: RAND State Statistics => Regional Economic Profiles // Descriptions: "Summary: Personal income, per capita personal income, total earnings, total employment, average earnings, and other categories"; "Additional Background: Regional economic profiles includes personal income, population, per capita personal income, total earnings, total employment, average earnings per job, and related categories.  Data are reported in current dollars.

Estimates for 2001 forward reflect the results of the comprehensive revision to the national income and product accounts (NIPAs) released in July 2013, creating a temporary break in BEA's time series for earlier years.
Cibola, NM was separated from Valencia in June 1981; Valencia includes Cibola through the end of 1981.

La Paz County, AZ was separated from Yuma County on January 1, 1983; The Yuma, AZ MSA contains the area that became La Paz County, AZ through 1982 and excludes it beginning with 1983
Shawano, WI and Menominee, WI are combined as Shawano (incl. Menominee), WI prior to 1989
Broomfield County, CO, was created from parts of Adams, Boulder, Jefferson, and Weld counties effective November 15, 2001; estimates for Broomfield county begin with 2002.
Estimates for 1979 forward reflect Alaska Census Areas as defined by the Census Bureau; those for prior years reflect Alaska Census Divisions as defined in the 1970 Decennial Census. Estimates from 1988 forward separate Aleutian Islands Census Area into Aleutians East Borough and Aleutians West Census Area. Estimates for 1991 forward separate Denali Borough from Yukon-Koyukuk Census Area and Lake and Peninsula Borough from Dillingham Census Area. Estimates from 1993 forward separate Skagway-Yakutat-Angoon Census Area into Skagway-Hoonah-Angoon Census Area and Yakutat Borough. Estimates from 2008 forward separate Skagway-Hoonah-Angoon Census Area into Skagway Borough and Hoonah-Angoon Census Area. Estimates from 2009 forward separate Wrangell-Petersburg Census Area into Petersburg Census Area and Wrangell City and Borough. In addition, a part of the Prince of Wales-Outer Ketchikan Census Area was annexed by Ketchikan Gateway Borough and part (Meyers Chuck Area) was included in the new Wrangell City and Borough. The remainder of the Prince of Wales-Outer Ketchikan Census Area was renamed Prince of Wales-Hyder Census Area
Virginia combination areas consist of one or two independent cities with 1980 populations of less than 100,000 combined with an adjacent county. The county name appears first, followed by the city name(s). Separate estimates for the jurisdictions making up the combination area are not available
Nonmetropolitan state portion includes micropolitan counties." // "Geographic Coverage: U.S., States, Counties. Periodicity: Annually

Series Begins/Ends: 1969 - 2016 // Note: "L = Less than $50,000, but the estimates for this item are included in the totals.NA = Not Available.NM = Not meaningful."; "Type of income divided by population yields a per capita measure for that type of income."

Data Source: Bureau of Economic Analysis" // for potentially useful information about per capita personal income, see https://www.bea.gov/news/2017/local-area-personal-income-2016, which seems to be talking about the same source of data as Regional Economic Profiles' one.
